Advanced date functions.

Building on the date basics, these functions handle the calendar tricks that reporting actually demands.

Date-truncate is the workhorse. Give it a unit — hour, day, or month — and it chops a timestamp down to that boundary. Truncating to the hour turns every timestamp in a given hour into the same value, which is exactly what you need to bucket transactions into hourly counts.

Last-day returns the final day of the month containing your date — useful for month-end reporting. Next-day jumps forward to the next named weekday, like the next Monday on or after a date. Quarter pulls out the calendar quarter, one through four. And week-of-year gives you the i-s-o week number.

The one with a subtlety is months-between. It returns the number of months between two dates, including a fractional part for partial months. So the elapsed tenure of a loan might come back as fourteen point five months, not just fourteen. When you need whole months, remember to floor or round the result yourself.

Together these turn fiddly calendar math into single function calls, which keeps reporting queries readable.
